observations.managementAction:
Management will have a supplemental to allocate funds for the recommendation and hire personnel who will facilitate the transfer of title of the land declared in the name of the Municipality. Funds are already allocated. However, there is still no personnel hired who will facilitate the transfer of title of the land declared in the name of the Municipality.
The Inventory Committee attended the seminar on One-Time Cleansing of PPE on October 26-27, 2023 to gain knowledge on the general and procedural guidelines of COA Circular 2020-006.
The Acting Municipal Treasurer and the Acting Municipal Accountant agreed to request and assign, as the case may be, personnel who will prepare and maintain updated property cards to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report;
Acting Municipal Accountant agreed to identify semi-expendable property which were recognized as PPE and reclassify to the affected appropriate semi-expendable inventory accounts (if not yet issued to end-user), expense accounts (if issued within the year) or accumulated surplus/deficit/retained earnings accounts (if issued in prior years) consistent with Section 5.4 of COA Circular No. 2016-006;
Inventory Committee agreed to pursue undertaking a one-time cleansing of PPE account balances and strictly comply with the guidelines and procedures enumerated in COA Circular No. 2020-006; and
Acting Municipal Treasurer agreed to (i) work for the registration and insurance coverage for all government motor vehicles owned by the Municipality; (ii) prepare motor vehicle profile indicating the date of acquisition, model/make/type and cost to determine those which have to be protected with insurance; and (iii) submit Property Inventory Form as basis for the assessment of general insurance coverage over all insurable assets, properties and interests with the Government Service Insurance System.

observations.recommendation:
We reiterated prior year’s recommendation and Management agreed to allocate fund for the expenses to secure copies of the title of the declared real properties and assign a focal person who will focus on the requirements needed to facilitate the immediate transfer of titles of the parcels of land under the name of the Municipality.
We also recommended and the:
(a) Acting Municipal Treasurer and the Acting Municipal Accountant agreed to request and assign, as the case may be, personnel who will prepare and maintain updated property cards to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report;
(b) Acting Municipal Accountant agreed to identify semi-expendable property which were recognized as PPE and reclassify to the affected appropriate semi-expendable inventory accounts (if not yet issued to end-user), expense accounts (if issued within the year) or accumulated surplus/deficit/retained earnings accounts (if issued in prior years) consistent with Section 5.4 of COA Circular No. 2016-006;
(c) Inventory Committee agreed to pursue undertaking a one-time cleansing of PPE account balances and strictly comply with the guidelines and procedures enumerated in COA Circular No. 2020-006; and
(d) Acting Municipal Treasurer agreed to (i) work for the registration and insurance coverage for all government motor vehicles owned by the Municipality; (ii) prepare motor vehicle profile indicating the date of acquisition, model/make/type and cost to determine those which have to be protected with insurance; and (iii) submit Property Inventory Form as basis for the assessment of general insurance coverage over all insurable assets, properties and interests with the Government Service Insurance System.

We recommended and Management agreed to –
i. ensure utilization and implementation of fund transfers both from LGUs and National Government Agencies;
ii. revert the unused balance to the Source Agency upon completion of the project of related trust fund accounts in compliance with Item 6.7 of COA Circular No. 94-013;
iii. ensure completeness of the supporting documents attached to the disbursement vouchers as mandated by Section 4(6) of PD 1445 and DOLE DO No. 239; and
iv. submit the necessary supporting documents to ensure the transparency and accountability of the distributed raw materials, tools and equipment to individuals and labor group in the implementation of Department of Labor and Employment (DOLE) Livelihood Programs for Disadvantaged Individuals or Labor organizations totaling ₱2,095,866.00.

We have recommended the following:
 That the Disbursing Officer/ Accountable Officers regularly submit the Report of Disbursements/Liquidation documents to the Accounting Office for timely recording in the books of accounts for fair presentation of the financial statements. Likewise, refund any unexpended balance of cash advance at the end of the year as prescribed under regulations;
 That the Municipal Accountant require the Disbursing Officer/ Accountable Officers to submit promptly the liquidation documents and shall record the liquidations on time to ensure that all transactions are included in the financial statements. Also, record liquidation only when properly supported with liquidation report and supporting documents;
 No cash advance should be granted to an accountable officer unless the previous cash advance given to him has been fully liquidated.

We have recommended the following:
 The MPDC/MENRO sees to it that henceforth, all relevant cost for the implementation of the SWMP is integrated to the Annual Budget as well as Annual Investment Plan. Coordination among the different offices is hereby advised;
 The Municipal Mayor convenes the SWMB and seeks justification as to the reason for the low success rate for the implementation of SWM projects;
 The members of the SWMB revisit the provisions of the IRR of R.A. No. 9003. Henceforth, implement quality assurance/ monitoring mechanism to facilitate an efficient and effective implementation of the programs indicated in the SWMP

We have recommended management to:
 seek a separate SB appropriation ordinance/resolution in cases of lump sum appropriations containing general terms, to serve as an authority to enter into contract in behalf of the Municipal Government in accordance to Section 22 (c) of R.A. No. 7160 and the applicable jurisprudence.;
 strictly comply with the provisions of DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1 in the preparation and utilization of the 20% DF to attain the desired socio-economic and environmental outcomes;
 instruct the Municipal Engineer to consult the duly prepared Annual Procurement Plan (APP) for infrastructure projects if any (for unimplemented projects), since said report include the timeline for the implementation of the project. Justification as to the reason for the non-implementation should also be sought to the responsible persons; and,
 instruct the BAC/Municipal Accountant/Treasurer to immediately submit contract documents and other necessary documents for proper review and evaluation of the said projects funded under the 20% Development Fund.

We have recommended Management that:

the Bids and Awards Committee should strictly comply with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 in the conduct of public bidding and awarding of contracts/ projects.  BAC members, BAC secretariat and the TWG should familiarize themselves with different rules and regulations set forth by R.A. No. 9184;
Submit a copy of the duly approved APP that includes procurement for infrastructure projects for CY 2015, if any.  Henceforth, an APP should be prepared and approved before any procurement is made and should be duly submitted for review and verification;
Adhere to the transparency provision as this is one of the governing principles on government procurement;  
BAC should invite observers in all stages of the procurement process;
Ensure that prospective bidders submit complete eligibility requirements and post the necessary bid security before they are marked as “passed” and declared as LCB;
Require the prospective bidders post the required performance security prior to contract signing;  
Copy of the contract documents be submitted to the Office of the Auditor within five (5) working days from issuance in the standard form as prescribed by GPPB and as required under  COA Circular 2009-001 for auditorial and technical review; 
BAC should submit written justification/s for non-adherence to provisions of R.A. No. 9184.

We have recommended that:
the appropriation in the SEF Local School Board Budget and/or Resolution expressed in generic terms be supported with detail as to the projects and activities and cost to be funded by SEF for proper evaluation and monitoring of fund utilization.  Henceforth, ensure that Special Education Funds be spent specifically in fulfillment of the purpose for which the fund was created as determined and approved by the Local School Board;
the above-enumerated lacking documents be submitted for proper review and evaluation of the said projects funded under SEF;
the prescribed rules and regulations on processing of disbursements be strictly observed.   Henceforth, ensure that all disbursements are properly obligated and supported with complete documentation before payments are made; and
the Municipal Accountant take extra-care in recording transactions and prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to present fairly the financial statements.

We have recommended that management direct the -
Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Budget Officer to regularly reconcile their records to ensure the completeness and accuracy of recorded amortizations and bank charges;
Municipal Treasurer see to it that all billing statements and debit memos (DM) pertaining to loans shall be furnished to the Budget Office for the covering Obligation Request; ensure that all loan amortizations and other financial charges are recorded in the cashbook; and submit all Billing Statements and DM supported with ObR to the Accounting Office for recording in the books of accounts;
Municipal Budget Officer to provide Obligation Request for the loan amortization payments and record them accordingly in the registry.  Maintain registry to serve as common reference to facilitate reconciliation of records;
Municipal Government to, henceforth, ensure that the appropriation intended for loans and other contractual obligations are sufficient enough to cover such obligations, as mandated in Section 303 of R.A. No. 7160; and see to it that the appropriation shall be used solely for its purpose.

We have recommend that Management:

Require the conduct of complete annual physical count of PPE in accordance with  Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Vol. 1;
Invite a representative of the Auditor to witness the inventory taking for this purpose;
Require the maintenance of complete and accurate Equipment Ledger Cards/ PPELC for each inventory item pursuant to Section 488 (d) of the GAAM and the NGAS in order to promote effective monitoring and controls over PPE;
Require the reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records after the physical count;
Physical Inventory Reports shall be submitted to the Property Officer and COA Office for verification and reconciliation of the result of the physical inventory with the complete Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and the Property Cards maintained by the Accounting Office and Property Unit, respectively;
Require the renewal of Acknowledgment Receipt of Equipment (ARE) every three years or every time there is a change in accountability in accordance with the Instructions of the Use of ARE as provided by NGAS Manual for LGUs;
Comply with the prescribed procedures in COA Circular No. 89-296 on disposal of unserviceable PPE, if any.
